boot: Add paging support for boot menu to prevent scroll overflow

When the boot menu contains too many entries, the previous implementation would
print all entries sequentially, causing early entries to scroll off-screen. This
made top-priority boot devices invisible to users, defeating the purpose of the
boot menu. Users could not see how to choose the devices that scrolled away.

This change implements two-page navigation with Enter key switching. If the
quantity of boot menu entries exceeds BOOTMENU_PAGE_SIZE (18), entries are split
across two pages with a page indicator in the header. All entries remain
selectable by their keyboard key regardless of visible page. TPM menu ('m' key)
remains accessible from any page. A new helper function display_menu_page()
eliminates code duplication between initial display and refresh operations.

This ensures all boot devices remain visible, supporting up to 35 boot menu
entries (plus TPM) while keeping the menu readable on 80x25 text mode displays.

Signed-off-by: Mike Banon <mikebdp2@gmail.com>
